To decide the first query for each of the 8 given black-box functions, I used a Bayesian optimisation strategy based on a Gaussian Process (GP) as the surrogate model 
fitted to the data, and the Upper Confidence Bound (UCB) as the acquisition function to guide query selection, with β = 1.96 (95% confidence interval), which is balanced 
between exploitation and exploration. Similarity between the data points was measured using the Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel, with a length-scale of 0.1xD (D = no. 
of dimensions for input variables) for all functions, except for function 8. For the latter, Automatic Relevance Determination (ARD) was applied to the RBF, to assign 
independent length-scales to each input dimension. For all functions with >=3 dimensions (function 3 onwards), I used Sobol sampling rather than random sampling to 
generate the grid search space in a uniform, structured, space-filling and highly performing way and support a fast and effective Bayesian optimisation process when 
working with high-dimensional spaces. For functions 1 and 2 (2D), I used a grid to evaluate the acquisition function.
